<font color="#FF0000">INHERITANCE</font><br>
<tt>Thu May  8  5:29:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Well hello.  First: this site dialog is part of a new paradigm in human communication.  I think it is significant and appropriate that us Nam vets are members of the point team.  Second: In my experience the Wall allows Vietnam veterans to discover who they really are.  Some may say they don't need to go to no Wall to find out nothing.  When you go to the Wall there's really no one there but you and a list of names on granite.  When you return after your visit you remember so many friends and comrades you met while you were there standing alone.  I myself tried to go visit the Wall in a calm rational manner.  I planned to have the time to myself.  However, my family would not leave my side.  At the time my daughters were 16 and 6.  Also, my wife was right there.  If there ever could have been a generation gap between me and my kids that visit to the Wall configured it out the door.  I guess an analogy of what a Wall experience means to Nam vets can be described in this way.  When you have to deal with a millionaire in an economic situation you have to take all that money into consideration.  In the same way when you deal with a Nam veteran who's been to the Wall in a social situation you have to take all his or her affiliations into account.  I apologize for the weakness of this comparison.  But it does point in the right direction.  Oh well, enough time and space.  M.C. Bey
